Redundancy Filter in Genesis: What It Does and Why
It Matters
 What is the Redundancy Filter?
The Redundancy Filter is a built-in feature in Genesis that helps prevent a flood of similar alarms from the same
camera or sensor being sent repeatedly to the cloud. It ensures that only one alarm is sent within a specific time
window — by default, 30 seconds.
This feature helps operators focus on meaningful alerts without being overwhelmed, and reduces unnecessary
cloud traffic, bandwidth, and storage usage.
🎯 Why is this useful?
https://helpdesk.nxgen.io/portal/en/kb/articles/redundancy
✅ Avoids alert fatigue for operators
✅ Prevents cloud overload with duplicate alarms
✅ Ensures alarms sent are actionable and meaningful
✅ Helps maintain system performance and bandwidth
🔍 How does it work?
Let’s say the redundancy filter is set to 30 seconds:
1. A camera or sensor sends a video alarm to Genesis.
2. Genesis accepts the first alarm.
3. If another alarm from the same camera with the same alarm code is received within 30 seconds, it will be
automatically rejected.
4. After the 30-second window ends, a new alarm from that camera will again be accepted.
This logic is applied per camera, so each stream is handled independently.
🧠 Example
12:00:00 → Camera A sends motion alarm → ✅ Accepted
12:00:20 → Camera A sends another motion alarm → ❌ Rejected
12:00:31 → Camera A sends another motion alarm → ✅ Accepted
⚠️ Important Notes for Device Configuration
Devices should be configured to not send alarms too frequently, especially if the alarm logic is sensitive
(e.g., movement, line crossing).
Genesis does not block alarms at the device — only at the cloud ingest stage — so local device logs may
still show all events.
